{
  "The correct sequence of events at the neuromuscular junction leading to contraction is:": "",
  "Contraction, ACh release, Ca2+ release, action potential": "",
  "Ca2+ release, ACh release, contraction, action potential": "",
  "Nerve AP arrives, ACh released, binds receptors, muscle AP generated, Ca2+ released from SR, contraction": "",
  "The events occur randomly with no specific order": "",
  "The complete signaling pathway proceeds in a strict sequence: a nerve action potential triggers ACh release, ACh binds to receptors on the motor end plate, generating a muscle action potential that travels along the sarcolemma and into T-tubules, triggering Ca2+ release from the SR to initiate cross-bridge cycling.": "",
  "Calcium ions for muscle contraction are released from the:": "",
  "The nerve terminal": "",
  "Sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR)": "",
  "Mitochondria": "",
  "T-tubules": "",
  "The sarcoplasmic reticulum stores calcium in its terminal cisternae at high concentrations; when an action potential reaches the T-tubule, it activates voltage-sensitive dihydropyridine receptors that trigger ryanodine receptors on the SR to open, releasing Ca2+ into the sarcoplasm.": "",
  "The size principle of motor unit recruitment states that:": "",
  "All motor units fire simultaneously regardless of force needed": "",
  "Smaller motor units are recruited first, with progressively larger units added as more force is needed": "",
  "The largest motor units are always recruited first": "",
  "Motor units are recruited randomly": "",
  "The size principle (Henneman's principle) states that motor neurons are recruited in order of increasing size: small motor neurons with low thresholds innervating slow-twitch fibers are recruited first for fine motor control, and larger motor neurons innervating fast-twitch fibers are added only when greater force is required.": "",
  "The length-tension relationship shows maximum force production occurs when:": "",
  "There is no actin-myosin overlap": "",
  "Sarcomeres are at their optimal resting length with maximal actin-myosin overlap": "",
  "The muscle is stretched to its maximum length": "",
  "The muscle is completely compressed": "",
  "The length-tension relationship demonstrates that maximum isometric force is generated when sarcomeres are at their optimal resting length (approximately 2.0-2.6 micrometers), where the greatest number of cross-bridges can form between overlapping actin and myosin filaments.": "",
  "Type I (slow-twitch) muscle fibers are rich in:": "",
  "Mitochondria and myoglobin, making them appear red": "",
  "Fast glycolytic enzymes": "",
  "Glycogen stores only": "",
  "No distinguishing features": "",
  "Type I fibers contain abundant mitochondria for aerobic ATP production and high concentrations of myoglobin (an oxygen-storing protein), giving them their characteristic red color and making them highly fatigue-resistant for endurance activities.": "",
  "Type IIb (fast-twitch glycolytic) fibers are best suited for:": "",
  "Maintaining upright posture through prolonged low-intensity contractions": "",
  "Short, explosive bursts of power such as sprinting or jumping": "",
  "Long-distance aerobic swimming and sustained endurance efforts": "",
  "Marathon running and other sustained oxidative endurance activities": "",
  "Type IIb (or IIx) fibers have the fastest contraction speed, largest diameter, and greatest force production, relying primarily on anaerobic glycolysis; they fatigue rapidly but are ideal for activities requiring brief, maximal power output like sprinting, jumping, and throwing.": "",
  "Wave summation occurs when:": "",
  "Stimuli are separated by hours or days": "",
  "The muscle fully relaxes between each stimulus": "",
  "A second stimulus arrives before the muscle fully relaxes from the first, producing greater total force": "",
  "Only one motor unit is activated": "",
  "Wave summation (temporal summation) occurs when successive stimuli arrive at a frequency that does not allow complete relaxation between twitches, so each new contraction builds upon the residual tension of the previous one, producing progressively greater total force.": "",
  "Treppe (the staircase effect) describes:": "",
  "The immediate maximal force from the first contraction": "",
  "A decrease in force with each successive contraction": "",
  "Complete tetanus from rapid stimulation": "",
  "A progressive increase in contraction strength with repeated stimuli at low frequency, as the muscle warms up": "",
  "Treppe is the phenomenon where successive muscle twitches at the same stimulus intensity produce progressively stronger contractions, resulting from increased availability of Ca2+ in the sarcoplasm, increased enzyme activity from warming, and improved muscle fiber compliance, which is why athletes warm up before competition.": "",
  "Complete (fused) tetanus differs from incomplete (unfused) tetanus in that:": "",
  "Complete tetanus is weaker than incomplete tetanus because the sustained fusion of stimuli fatigues the available cross-bridges over time": "",
  "Incomplete tetanus involves no meaningful contraction because the gaps between stimuli prevent any useful summation of force": "",
  "Complete tetanus produces a smooth, sustained contraction with no relaxation between stimuli, while incomplete tetanus shows partial relaxation between stimuli": "",
  "There is no physiological difference between complete and incomplete tetanus; both produce the same contractile force and relaxation pattern": "",
  "In incomplete (unfused) tetanus, the stimulus frequency allows brief partial relaxation between contractions, producing a wavy force tracing; in complete (fused) tetanus, the frequency is so high that no relaxation occurs, producing a smooth, plateau of maximum sustainable force.": "",
  "Curare causes muscle paralysis by:": "",
  "Competitively blocking nicotinic ACh receptors on the motor end plate, preventing depolarization": "",
  "Increasing ACh release at the NMJ": "",
  "Increasing calcium release from the SR": "",
  "Destroying the sarcoplasmic reticulum": "",
  "Curare is a competitive antagonist that binds to nicotinic ACh receptors at the NMJ without activating them, blocking acetylcholine from binding and preventing depolarization of the motor end plate, resulting in flaccid paralysis, particularly dangerous when it affects the respiratory muscles.": "",
  "What is the length-tension relationship in muscle physiology?": "",
  "The relationship between a muscle's resting sarcomere length and the maximum isometric force it can generate, determined by the degree of actin-myosin overlap": "",
  "The relationship between the number of muscle fibers and total body weight": "",
  "The relationship between nerve length and signal speed": "",
  "The relationship between muscle length and the speed of contraction": "",
  "The length-tension relationship describes how the isometric force a muscle can produce depends on its initial sarcomere length; at optimal length, maximum actin-myosin overlap allows the most cross-bridges to form, producing peak force, while overstretched or over-compressed sarcomeres produce less force.": "",
  "What is motor unit recruitment?": "",
  "The process of activating progressively more motor units to increase the force of whole-muscle contraction": "",
  "The process of building new motor neurons through exercise": "",
  "The replacement of damaged motor neurons after injury": "",
  "The deactivation of motor units during rest": "",
  "Motor unit recruitment is the nervous system's primary mechanism for grading whole-muscle force by activating increasing numbers of motor units; since individual fibers follow the all-or-none law, force gradation depends on how many motor units are activated simultaneously.": "",
  "What is a depolarizing neuromuscular blocker?": "",
  "A drug that permanently increases muscle contraction strength by enhancing the sensitivity of actin-myosin cross-bridges to calcium, producing larger forces with each cycle": "",
  "A drug like succinylcholine that initially activates (depolarizes) the motor end plate, then causes sustained depolarization and receptor desensitization, leading to temporary paralysis": "",
  "A drug that selectively blocks voltage-gated calcium channels in cardiac muscle only, reducing heart rate and contraction strength without any effect on skeletal muscle": "",
  "A vitamin supplement that enhances nerve conduction velocity at the neuromuscular junction, improving the speed and reliability of signal transmission to muscle fibers": "",
  "Depolarizing neuromuscular blockers like succinylcholine mimic ACh by binding to nicotinic receptors and causing initial depolarization (producing brief fasciculations), but because they resist breakdown by acetylcholinesterase, they produce sustained depolarization that desensitizes the receptors, resulting in flaccid paralysis used during surgical intubation.": "",
  "What is the 'size principle' (Henneman's size principle)?": "",
  "Muscle fiber size determines the speed of contraction but not force": "",
  "Larger muscles always produce more force than smaller muscles": "",
  "Motor neurons are recruited in order of increasing size: smaller, slow-twitch motor units first, then larger, fast-twitch motor units as greater force is demanded": "",
  "The largest motor units are always active, regardless of force requirement": "",
  "Henneman's size principle states that motor neurons are recruited in an orderly fashion based on their size (and therefore threshold): small-diameter alpha motor neurons (innervating Type I fibers) are recruited first at low force levels, and progressively larger neurons (innervating Type II fibers) are added as more force is needed.": "",
  "What is the difference between isometric and isotonic contractions?": "",
  "They are the same type of contraction with different names": "",
  "Isometric means the muscle lengthens; isotonic means it shortens": "",
  "In isometric contractions, force is generated without muscle length change; in isotonic contractions, the muscle changes length while maintaining relatively constant tension": "",
  "Isometric contractions only occur in smooth muscle; isotonic only in skeletal": "",
  "Isometric ('same length') contractions generate force without changing muscle length (like holding a plank), while isotonic ('same tension') contractions involve muscle length changes against a constant load, including concentric (shortening) and eccentric (lengthening) subtypes.": "",
  "What does 'threshold stimulus' mean in muscle physiology?": "",
  "The stimulus needed to recruit every motor unit in the body simultaneously": "",
  "The maximum stimulus a muscle can receive before damage occurs": "",
  "The minimum stimulus strength required to depolarize a muscle fiber enough to generate an action potential and trigger contraction": "",
  "The stimulus that causes a muscle to relax completely": "",
  "The threshold stimulus is the minimum voltage (or stimulus strength) needed to depolarize a muscle fiber to the critical level that opens enough voltage-gated sodium channels to generate a self-propagating action potential, which then triggers the full contraction response according to the all-or-none principle.": "",
  "What is the latent period of a muscle twitch?": "",
  "The relaxation phase after contraction": "",
  "The recovery period between two separate exercise sessions": "",
  "The period of maximum force generation": "",
  "The brief delay between the stimulus and the onset of contraction, during which excitation-contraction coupling occurs": "",
  "The latent period is the short delay (typically 1-2 milliseconds) between the delivery of the stimulus and the beginning of visible contraction, during which the action potential propagates along the sarcolemma and T-tubules, Ca2+ is released from the SR, and cross-bridges begin to form.": "",
  "What is the role of the dihydropyridine receptor (DHPR) in excitation-contraction coupling?": "",
  "It serves as an active calcium pump on the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane that resequesters calcium ions during the relaxation phase of muscle contraction": "",
  "It functions as an enzyme at the neuromuscular junction that rapidly breaks down acetylcholine after it has bound to the motor end plate receptors": "",
  "It is a voltage-sensitive receptor on the T-tubule membrane that detects the action potential and triggers the ryanodine receptor on the SR to release calcium": "",
  "It forms the structural cross-bridge connection between the actin thin filament and the myosin thick filament during the power stroke of contraction": "",
  "The dihydropyridine receptor (DHPR) is a voltage-gated calcium channel/sensor embedded in the T-tubule membrane that undergoes a conformational change when the action potential arrives, mechanically triggering the associated ryanodine receptor (RyR) on the SR membrane to open and release stored calcium into the sarcoplasm.": "",
  "What is the ryanodine receptor (RyR)?": "",
  "A protein that breaks down ATP to power the myosin head": "",
  "A regulatory protein on the thin filament": "",
  "A calcium release channel on the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane that opens in response to DHPR activation, flooding the sarcoplasm with Ca2+": "",
  "A receptor on the motor end plate that binds ACh": "",
  "The ryanodine receptor is a large calcium release channel embedded in the SR membrane that opens when activated by the DHPR on the adjacent T-tubule, allowing the rapid efflux of stored calcium from the SR into the sarcoplasm to initiate the contraction process.": "",
  "What does 'summation of force' mean in whole-muscle physiology?": "",
  "The progressive decrease in force-generating capacity during repeated contractions, caused by the accumulation of metabolic waste products in the sarcoplasm": "",
  "The combining of forces from multiple motor units (spatial summation) and/or from rapid successive stimuli (temporal summation) to produce graded force in a whole muscle": "",
  "The generation of contractile force by a single motor unit functioning in isolation, independent of any recruitment of additional motor units or frequency changes": "",
  "The baseline resting tension present in a completely relaxed muscle due to the inherent elasticity of the connective tissue elements and passive sarcolemma resistance": "",
  "Force summation in whole muscles occurs through two mechanisms: spatial summation (recruiting more motor units to increase total force) and temporal summation (increasing stimulus frequency so twitches overlap and add together), allowing smooth, graded control of muscle force from delicate tasks to maximal efforts.": "",
  "A student is studying for the AP exam and encounters this question: 'A patient is given a drug that blocks voltage-gated sodium channels on the sarcolemma. Predict the effect on muscle contraction.' What is the correct answer and reasoning?": "",
  "Muscle contraction would be prevented because the action potential cannot propagate along the sarcolemma and into T-tubules, so Ca2+ would not be released from the SR": "",
  "The muscle would contract continuously without the ability to relax": "",
  "Only cardiac muscle would be affected; skeletal muscle would function normally": "",
  "Contraction would be stronger because more sodium would accumulate inside the fiber": "",
  "Blocking voltage-gated sodium channels prevents action potential generation and propagation on the sarcolemma; without an action potential reaching the T-tubules, DHPRs cannot activate, RyRs remain closed, calcium stays sequestered in the SR, and no cross-bridge cycling occurs, resulting in muscle paralysis.": "",
  "An AP exam free-response question asks: 'Explain why a muscle produces less force when it is either overstretched or over-compressed compared to its optimal resting length.' How should a student structure their answer using the length-tension relationship?": "",
  "The muscle only produces force at one exact sarcomere length of 2.2 micrometers and produces zero force at all other lengths, because cross-bridges can only form at this single precise overlap distance between actin and myosin": "",
  "Force depends only on the number of motor units recruited and the frequency of stimulation, not on sarcomere length, because cross-bridge formation is independent of the degree of overlap between actin and myosin": "",
  "At any length, the muscle produces the same force because all available cross-bridges always form regardless of filament overlap, since myosin heads can reach actin binding sites at any distance between the thick and thin filaments": "",
  "When overstretched, actin and myosin have reduced overlap so fewer cross-bridges form; when over-compressed, filaments collide and interfere with each other, also reducing cross-bridge formation; optimal length provides maximum overlap for maximum cross-bridges and force": "",
  "The length-tension relationship is based on the sliding filament theory: at optimal resting length, the maximum number of myosin heads can interact with actin; when overstretched, reduced overlap means fewer cross-bridges; when over-compressed, thick filaments crumple against Z-lines and thin filaments overlap each other, sterically hindering cross-bridge formation.": "",
  "During a laboratory experiment, a student applies increasingly rapid electrical stimuli to an isolated muscle. She observes that individual twitches begin to merge, then fuse into a smooth contraction. The professor asks her to explain the transition from twitches to unfused tetanus to fused tetanus at the molecular level.": "",
  "The muscle switches from skeletal to cardiac-type contractile behavior at high stimulation frequencies, adopting the autorhythmic properties and gap-junction-mediated conduction that are characteristic of cardiac tissue": "",
  "Higher stimulus frequencies trigger the formation of new motor units within the muscle by activating previously non-innervated muscle fibers and establishing new neuromuscular junctions": "",
  "At higher frequencies, Ca2+ accumulates in the sarcoplasm because the SR cannot resequester it fast enough between stimuli, maintaining cross-bridge cycling and producing sustained, increasing force": "",
  "The transitions from twitch to tetanus occur because the muscle physically grows larger with each successive stimulus, adding new sarcomeres and myofibrils that increase force capacity": "",
  "As stimulus frequency increases, there is insufficient time for the Ca2+-ATPase pumps to fully return calcium to the SR between stimuli; this progressive calcium accumulation in the sarcoplasm keeps more actin binding sites exposed and more cross-bridges cycling continuously, producing the smooth, sustained maximum force of complete tetanus.": "",
  "A pharmacology question on the AP exam asks: 'An organophosphate pesticide inhibits acetylcholinesterase. Trace the cascade of events from the NMJ to the muscle fiber and predict the clinical outcome.' What is the correct analysis?": "",
  "ACh levels in the synaptic cleft would decrease rapidly because the organophosphate stimulates acetylcholinesterase to work faster, causing muscles to relax completely due to insufficient stimulation at the motor end plate": "",
  "ACh accumulates in the synaptic cleft, causing continuous end-plate depolarization, sustained muscle stimulation, fasciculations, then depolarization block and flaccid paralysis, potentially fatal if respiratory muscles are affected": "",
  "The muscle would strengthen and improve its contractile performance because the prolonged presence of ACh at the motor end plate would enhance excitation-contraction coupling efficiency and increase maximum force output": "",
  "Only smooth muscle in the walls of hollow organs would be affected because skeletal muscle at the neuromuscular junction uses a different neurotransmitter system that is not influenced by cholinesterase": "",
  "Acetylcholinesterase inhibition causes ACh to accumulate, producing continuous receptor activation, sustained end-plate depolarization, initial muscle fasciculations and cramping, followed by depolarization block (receptor desensitization) leading to flaccid paralysis; this sequence affects all cholinergic synapses and is life-threatening when respiratory muscles are paralyzed.": "",
  "An AP integration question asks: 'Compare and contrast the mechanisms by which curare and botulinum toxin both cause muscle paralysis, despite working at different sites of the NMJ.' What is the correct comparison?": "",
  "Curare increases the amount of ACh released from the presynaptic terminal by enhancing vesicle fusion, while botulinum toxin increases the sensitivity of postsynaptic nicotinic receptors, producing excessive stimulation": "",
  "Neither drug affects the neuromuscular junction at all; both curare and botulinum toxin act directly on the sarcomere by binding to and inhibiting the myosin ATPase enzyme, preventing the power stroke cycle": "",
  "Both drugs work identically by triggering apoptosis of the motor neuron cell body, leading to irreversible denervation of the muscle fiber and permanent loss of voluntary contraction in the affected muscles": "",
  "Curare blocks ACh receptors on the motor end plate (postsynaptic), while botulinum toxin prevents ACh release from the nerve terminal (presynaptic); both ultimately prevent muscle depolarization and produce flaccid paralysis": "",
  "Though both produce flaccid paralysis, they act at different points: botulinum toxin acts presynaptically by cleaving SNARE proteins to prevent ACh vesicle fusion and release, while curare acts postsynaptically as a competitive antagonist that occupies nicotinic receptors without activating them, preventing ACh from binding.": "",
  "A practice AP question states: 'During rigor mortis, the cross-bridges are locked. Explain at the molecular level why the muscles become stiff, and predict what would happen if ATP were artificially supplied to the muscle after rigor has set in.'": "",
  "Without ATP, myosin heads cannot detach from actin after the power stroke, creating permanent cross-bridges; if ATP were supplied, it would bind to myosin heads, releasing the cross-bridges and causing the muscles to relax": "",
  "Rigor mortis is caused solely by excess calcium flooding the sarcoplasm after death, which triggers uncontrolled cross-bridge cycling; supplying ATP would have no effect because the calcium overload is the primary problem": "",
  "Rigor occurs because excess ATP production continues after death and locks the myosin heads onto actin in a permanent bound state; removing this accumulated ATP from the muscle would release the cross-bridges and allow relaxation": "",
  "ATP has absolutely no relationship to rigor mortis or cross-bridge cycling; the stiffness after death is caused entirely by the denaturation of structural proteins in the sarcomere that lock the muscle into a rigid state": "",
  "After death, ATP depletion means myosin heads cannot detach from actin (since ATP binding is required for cross-bridge release), and calcium leaks from the SR, allowing cross-bridges to form and lock; supplying ATP would bind to myosin heads, break the cross-bridges, and allow relaxation.": "",
  "An AP exam scenario describes an athlete who can pick up a feather gently and also lift a 200-pound barbell. The question asks: 'Since individual muscle fibers follow the all-or-none principle, explain how the nervous system produces such dramatically different force levels.'": "",
  "Individual fibers can produce variable amounts of force depending on the task": "",
  "Different muscles are used for light vs. heavy tasks, so no gradation is needed": "",
  "The nervous system grades force by varying the number of motor units recruited (spatial summation) and the frequency of stimulation (temporal summation), not by varying the strength of individual fiber contractions": "",
  "The all-or-none principle does not actually apply to human muscles": "",
  "Although each fiber contracts maximally once threshold is reached, the nervous system controls whole-muscle force through spatial summation (recruiting few motor units for light tasks and many for heavy ones, following the size principle) and temporal summation (increasing firing frequency to achieve tetanus), enabling smooth force gradation from feather-light to maximum effort.": "",
  "An AP practice question asks: 'A patient has a mutation that makes the Ca2+-ATPase (SERCA) pump on the SR work at 50% efficiency. Predict the effects on muscle contraction and relaxation.' How should this be answered?": "",
  "The muscle would never be able to contract at all because the Ca2+-ATPase pump is required for the initial release of calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, and without a functioning pump no calcium would ever reach troponin": "",
  "Relaxation would be slowed because calcium cannot be efficiently returned to the SR; this would prolong contraction time, increase susceptibility to cramps, and could cause the muscle to fatigue more quickly from excessive cross-bridge cycling": "",
  "Contraction would be significantly weaker because the Ca2+-ATPase pump is needed to concentrate calcium in the SR before release, but the relaxation phase would proceed normally since it depends on passive diffusion": "",
  "Both contraction and relaxation would be completely normal because the Ca2+-ATPase pump plays only a minor supplementary role in calcium handling and other transport mechanisms would fully compensate for the reduced efficiency": "",
  "Impaired SERCA pump function means calcium removal from the sarcoplasm is slowed; troponin remains activated longer, actin binding sites stay exposed, and cross-bridges continue cycling longer than normal, resulting in prolonged contraction, delayed relaxation, increased ATP consumption, accelerated fatigue, and predisposition to muscle cramps.": "",
  "For AP exam preparation, a student must explain why the warmup treppe effect demonstrates the importance of temperature on enzyme activity in muscle physiology. What is the correct molecular explanation?": "",
  "Repeated contractions raise intracellular temperature, increasing the activity of enzymes like myosin ATPase and Ca2+-ATPase, making Ca2+ available more readily and ATP hydrolysis more efficient, producing progressively stronger contractions": "",
  "Temperature has no effect on muscle enzyme activity because the enzymes involved in contraction, including myosin ATPase and Ca2+-ATPase, maintain constant catalytic rates regardless of tissue temperature": "",
  "Treppe is caused by an increase in the number of sarcomeres added in series within each muscle fiber during repeated contractions, increasing the total length and force-generating capacity": "",
  "Treppe occurs because entirely new muscle fibers are created through rapid mitotic division during the warm-up period, increasing the total number of contractile units available for force": "",
  "The treppe effect demonstrates that mild increases in temperature from repeated contractions enhance enzyme kinetics (myosin ATPase cycles faster, Ca2+-ATPase pumps more efficiently) and increase calcium availability in the sarcoplasm, resulting in progressively stronger twitches until a steady state is reached, illustrating why athletes warm up before performance.": "",
  "A comprehensive AP review question asks: 'Trace the complete pathway from a motor neuron action potential to muscle fiber relaxation, identifying every key molecular event and the role of ATP at each step.' Which answer correctly identifies all critical steps?": "",
  "The process involves only three main phases: the nerve action potential reaches the muscle, the muscle contracts through an unspecified mechanism, and then the muscle relaxes when stimulation stops, with no intermediate molecular steps or calcium signaling events occurring between these broad phases": "",
  "Nerve AP reaches axon terminal, Ca2+ enters terminal, ACh released into cleft, ACh binds motor end plate receptors, muscle AP generated, AP travels along sarcolemma and into T-tubules, DHPR activates RyR, Ca2+ released from SR, Ca2+ binds troponin, tropomyosin shifts, cross-bridges form, power stroke (ADP+Pi released), ATP binds myosin for detachment, ATP hydrolyzed to recock head, cycle repeats; for relaxation: ACh broken down by AChE, stimulation ceases, Ca2+-ATPase pumps Ca2+ back into SR, troponin releases Ca2+, tropomyosin re-covers actin sites, cross-bridges cease": "",
  "The pathway from nerve signal to muscle contraction and relaxation differs for each individual person based on their unique genetics, muscle fiber type composition, and training history, making it impossible to summarize into one universal sequence": "",
  "The entire sequence from nerve to contraction consists of only three molecular steps: acetylcholine release from the nerve terminal, calcium binding to the contractile proteins, and a single power stroke, with just one molecule of ATP consumed during the whole cycle": "",
  "This comprehensive pathway includes every key step from neural signal to contraction to relaxation, and ATP plays roles at multiple points: energizing the myosin head (hydrolysis for cocking), breaking cross-bridges (binding for detachment), and powering relaxation (Ca2+-ATPase pumps to return calcium to the SR).": ""
}